title: Print Bed Level Test Anet Prusa

description.text:
This test is designed to show any deviation in distance between the nozzle and print bed throughout each adjustable corner to ensure quality, level prints. Save yourself some filament and use this test routinely to re-level your print bed.

For best results, stop print after the first layer and check homogeneity. A level bed will produce consistent texture, even if the nozzle is too close/far. Raise corners that appear "patchy" a quarter-turn at a time, then repeat test until satisfied. I find it better to raise the lower corners than lower the high corners, assuming you've already modded the z-endstop with a fine tuner.

Designed for a 220x220 mm build plate, but the object itself is 200x200x20 mm (perimeter) to leave clearance for the leveling screws.

This test helped me determine that my A8's aluminum heat bed was warped from the factory, so I just cut a piece of glass to clamp over top. I perform this test weekly and as needed. Additional file formats available upon request.

title: Beefed up prop guard for 5 inch props

description.text:
Designed for multi-rotors that use 5 inch props (or smaller). [250mm size]

I beefed up the prop guards a little bit. I print them in PETG [my new favorite filament type!] and they seem to work quite well.

I don't normally use prop guards, but it helps when I'm giving lessons to friends who are just learning to fly, or if I'm flying in a place with a lot of obstacles (trees etc.).

PETG seems to make these very flexible but sturdy enough; and the "beefing up" I did adds only a few grams to the original.

The arms are a bit thicker, added a middle-ring and a few more thinner arms for stability.

The screw holes will likely need to be enlarged slightly (a hobby knife will work well without sacrificing structural integrity), but they are designed to fit standard 16mmx19mm motor mounting holes.

UPDATE:

Seems that 2 of my slicer suites leave out part of the thin wall, so I made it a little bit thicker, and added some holes to reduce the weight. I haven't tried this one yet, let me know what you think!

Thanks to ppoinha for the original design.

description.text:
Hola! He diseñado el chasis de los drones F36/ H36 / E010 para sustituirlo en caso de que rompa. Para aumentar la vida del chasis, empecé concentrándome en la resistencia, pero después de unas cuantas pruebas, y un poco de práctica con el dron, ahora voy tras un chasis ligero.

  • Motores: Brushed 615. (6mm de diámetro y 15mm de largo)

Frame V6

Esta es la 6ª Versión que diseño, la cual sigue siendo muy similar al chasis original.
La principal innovación es la posición de la batería. Ahora se sitúa un poco más elevada respecto a las hélices. Así, al elevar el centro de masa del dron respecto a las hélices, conseguimos un dron algo menos estable pero más ágil. Esto es lo que busco ahora, conservando la Placa controladora del E010 sin modo acro.

Diferencias con el Chasis Original:

  • Centro de masa más elevado
  • 4 huecos para pasar los cables de motor
  • Un par de pestañas para aguantar la batería

Peso:

  • 6 gr aproximadamente en ABS.
  • Un poco más si está fabricado en PLA

Frame V7

Para el siguiente diseño, intentare romper un poco con el aspecto original, quitar la protección de hélices, y acercarme más a la geometría clásica de X de los drones de carreras.
Los soportes de motores necesitan cambiar. Quizas de una manera flexible (un circulo sin cerrar), los motores quedaran major fijados, sin necesidad de cortar o lijar los agujeros por fallos de impresion

Hi! I´m designing the F36/ H36 / E010 frame to replace it if it breaks. In order to enlarge the useful life of the frame, I started to focus on the hardness, but after a couple test, and more practice with the drone, I stay looking for a light frame.

  • The motor dimension in this drones are 6 mm diameter and 15mm long

Frame V6

This are the 6th version I´ve design, that it’s very similar than the original one.
The principal innovation is the position of the battery. Now it's a little bit moved up, The higher the center of mass the more agile the drone will be. That's what I'm looking for right now.

As difference whit the original, this frame has:

  • Different mass center
  • 4 holes to pass the motor cables.
  • A pair of tab to hold the battery.

Weight:

  • 6 gr approximately in ABS.
  • A little bit more if it´s PLA

Frame V7

Fort the next design I will break with the original aspect, get off the propellers protections, and go into something similar to classic carbon racing drone frames.
The motor holders need a change. Maybe with a flexible way (not a closed circle), the motors will fit better, without cutting or sanding the hole due to tolerance faults.
Also the motors need a lower protection in order to prevent cables from being scratched against the ground.

I hope you liked it and try it!!

title: optical endstop adjustment mechanism for Flsun Kossel Deltaprinter
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
i dont like and trust the mechanical endstops on my printer, so i bought some optical endstops.

I wanted to implement them with possibility to fine adjust the position of the optical endstop to get a well setup.

So i created this mechanism to fine adjust the position.

The whole part consits of flexible parts wich are directly printed in one step.
I think you will need an already well optimized setup to print the part in good quality.

I have spend some time to optimize the settings for my Printer.

I have printed with 0,1mm layer height and a 0,3 mm nozzle as an solid part without any support.

After printing you have to gently crack the connections to get a flexible part (hold with a fine tongue and do a gently rotation). In addition i have used some silicone spray to get less friction and better flexibility.

You will need a M3 Thread die and prepare the holes for the sensor, the main screw for adjustment as well as the uppest hole for fixing the holder by a screw.

As a spring i have used a standard ballpenspring.

Size of the screws you will need:

-M3x16 (for fixing the holder to the frame profile, i have used M3x20 because no was M3x16 was available)

-M3x30 (main adjustment screw)

-M3x12 (fixation screws for the sensor and also for the opposite part)

The small plastic washers wich you see on the picture are not needed and i dont use them actually. Backside of the Endstop boards are not plane but it is ok to screw them directly to the holder, there is some bending on the board but i rate it uncritical.

There is still some potential to optimize the design especially in aspect of tolerances, backlash etc. but for now my printer is working with it well.

Update
I have reworked the design and going to implement the new design to my printer.
I have already implemented the old design to my printer and the manual leveling for setup worked very well, but i was concerned about tolerance of the position during normal usage when some mechanical stress occur like accidently pushing/touching the endstops.

on new design the tolerance will be less and it will be possible to fix the sensor after manual level setup, so it will be more stable.

description.text: Print at 80% fill on ABS or PLA

Before paper was commonplace, the method for keeping your thoughts in order was the wax tablet. They're surprisingly easy to write on, and are capable of capturing almost the same level of detail as pen and paper. If you make a mistake you can use your finger or the rounded end of your stylus and smooth the wax back to blank again. There are three designs here,
a pocket 3 leaf version with spots for 4 'pages', (lasercut)
a large single tablet version for a notebook (CNC milled)
*a single page one reminiscent of modern technology. (lasercut) Here's some more information on wax tablets:
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wax_tablet

• Cut all the layers in your wood of choice and glue with PVA glue. If the wood surface is too smooth on the bottom you might have trouble with the wax not sticking to it. Milled pine worked for me, but lasercut ply was too smooth. Roughen it up with a sharp tool if you need to. Basically don't sand it.

  • Get the wax and colourant you're going to use. Darker colours work better as they provide the most contrast. I used a plain white candle from my local $2 shop, and a couple of jumbo crayons (purple, black, green and blue) mixed together until I was happy with the various colours.

  • Heat the wax in a metal pot. Some people use a double boiler to avoid overheating, but I used a hot air gun carefully and was happy with it. Just be really careful not to boil or bubble the wax and mix it thoroughly.

  • Start pouring the wax into the tablet. Pour only just enough to fill the base layer or less. I filled mine until about 75% of the wood was covered, then tilted the tablet to overcome surface tension and fill the rest. That way when the wax is cooled the surface will be a little below that of the wood, and unlikely to abrade away in your pocket, etc.

  • Let it cool for a few minutes. If there's too much wax in there you can scrape off the excess with a flat bit of wood across the top surface.

  • Let the wax cool thoroughly all the way through (might take half an hour or so). Then you can rub the top surface with a cloth or the rounded end of a stylus. This is also how you erase your tablet when it's full. (You don't really need to heat it to erase stuff. If it's in a really bad condition you can, though).
    • For a stylus, I've found an ordinary ball point pen works pretty well. I've got a four-colour one, and devoted the green colour to wax, so I don't have to carry a separate device to use the tablet. Lots of luck, love to see photos if anyone makes their own!

description.text:
Marlin 1.1.6 pour Dagoma DiscoEasy200 avec l'excellente tête de Z122. Avec paramètres plus ou moins semblables au firmware distribué par Dagoma, qui ne devrait pas trop dépayser les utilisateurs ayant l'habitude de celui-ci.

Le fichier hex peut s'installer directement avec la Dagom'App (Je configure mon imprimante > Je donne de nouveaux pouvoirs).

VERSION NON OFFICIELLE : Je me sens obligé de dire que vous l'installez à vos propres risques. C'est testé et ça marche chez moi, donc aucune raison que ça ne marche pas chez vous, cependant hors de question de venir me blâmer si quelque chose se passe mal.

Maintenant après avoir bien plombé l'ambiance, je vous souhaite beaucoup de bons prints avec ce firmware et espère que vous l'apprécierez :) Enjoy :)

UPDATE Marlin 1.1.6

Mis à jour avec la dernière version 1.1.6 de Marlin :

  • Les paramètres restent inchangés pour la grande majorité par rapport à la dernière version (qui n'était pas la 1.55 comme j'avais affiché mais bien la 1.1.5 - oops), par contre j'ai :
  • Activé le BABYSTEPPING. En gros, si on démarre son print et que boum, on se rend compte que l'offset pas bon - trop haut ou trop bas - hop, on double-clique la molette de l'écran et on se retrouve dans le menu BABYSTEPPING, qui permet en tournant la molette de remonter/redescendre en live (sans aucune latence) la tête sans influer sur déroulement du print !!! Plus besoin de recommencer, taper du gcode qui ne s'exécute pas immédiatement ou de maltraiter les coupleurs. Vraiment top.
  • Les sources de ma version sont maintenant sur mon repo GitHub, ce qui permettra une maintenance et mise à jour bien plus faciles et efficaces, et permet de visualiser facilement le code et ses différences par rapport au marlin de base (ce qui est une bonne aide pour apprendre à le configurer). Attention à bien sélectionner la branche "thingi" - les autres sont des modifications personnelles :
    https://github.com/JJJpnt/Marlin/tree/thingi

Hello, en fait les valeurs que tu hardcode dans le firmwares sont les valeurs par défaut.
Tu peux aussi les changer par gcode (ou écran), et les enregistrer dans la mémoire EPROM de la carte.
Et quand tu reflashes le firmware, l'EPROM en général reste inchangée. Donc tu as toujours tes vieux paramètres.
Les commandes :
Pour mettre les steps du z ) 400 : M92 Z400
 Pour enregistrer les valeurs dans l'eprom (sinon elles resautent aux précédentes quand tu redémarre l'imprimante) : M500
Pour visualiser les paramètres actuellement enregistrés dans l'eprom : M503
 Pour remettre l'eprom à zéro (et donc passer aux valeurs hardcodées dans le firmware) M502
(Si tu fais un M502, je te conseille de faire un M503 d'abord et de copier coller ça dans un coin au cas où, on sait jamais, car dans l'eprom y'a aussi les accélérations, jerk, etc... donc si tu débutes ça fait un peu beaucoup à avaler d'un coup et si jamais ça marchait moins bien tu pourras savoir les valeurs précédents et donc comment revenir en arrière).

title: LED Strip Fixture for Prusa Mk2S (non-restrictive)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
A nice led strip fixture for Prusa i3 Original MK2S.

Does not restrict extruder movement

This lighting solutions uses a popular self adhesive 12V LED strip (see image).

Can be installed to use the printer's own 12V supply.

See Post-Printing UPDATE below

Please post a Make if you make this!

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

i3 MK2S

Resolution:

200

Infill:

40%

Notes:

Printed in PETG.

The model file for the brackets is for the left side one. The right side bracket should be a mirror image of the left one. Do this in your slicer and save as a separate gcode-file (for Slic3r the procedure is Object => Mirror => Along X). This is mostly aesthetics, you should have no problem using two identical brackets, the light fixture would just not be exactly centered over the heatbed.

The MK42 heatbed is 25x21cm, so you'll have to print the fixture diagonally. Recommend a rotation of 39° (Slic3r: Rotate => around Z => 39)

Cut the LED strip to length and tape to the bottom of the fixture. Make sure the connection terminal of the LED strip is accessible through the hole.

Snap the fixture into place in the brackets. Slide the brackets onto the frame so that the brackets are parallel to each other. Move Z all the way up and X all the way left and right. Nothing should touch, but the zip ties holding the bearings come very close. If they touch the brackets on your printer, just use a file or some sand paper on the bracket until you have clearance.

Now either use a separate power supply for the LED strip, or steal power from the printer's PSU. The MK2S PSU conveniently has an unused plus/minus terminal under the plastic cover. Only do this if you know how, and with the power cord removed from the printer!

Lastly, neatly attach the cable to the right side bracket with (drumroll...) zip ties!

UPDATE

One end of the LED strip started to hang down after a few days. Maybe the 3M adhesive surface wasn't completely fresh, or maybe it just doesn't stick so well to PETG. I fixed this by adding aluminum foil tape to the inner sides of the fixture, so that it overlaps the sides of the LED strip. This should work, as the aluminum tape seems to stick very well. Also it has the added benefit of reflecting light a lot better than the black plastic. See the last pic.

description.text:
Side panels to go along with Peaberry's Kossel Base Stand. The rendered version is fit for the BIQU Kossel Plus along with Peaberry's stands. It's 345mm long, 52mm high, 1mm thick, has a 3mm ridge on the front, and a 10mm ridge on the back for stability and printability.

To attach this panel to the feet, you'll need 6 M3 bolts.

If you want to print panels in a different length, thickness, etc., I've also included the SCAD file, which is mostly parameterized and appears to work with Customizer. I have not yet tried printing one with fan and power block cutouts, so I can't recommend support settings yet. I'll update this Thing after I've made some successful prints with cutouts.

Notes:

If you're printing this on the same machine it will go on, you'll need to print as a tower since it'll be longer than your bed is wide.

You need support under the notch on the bottom end when printing. Setting slic3r to put support only on the base plate worked well to support the notch without filling in the screw holes.

You'll want to print with a substantial brim for added stability. I used a 10mm brim when printing mine.
The tower should be pretty structurally sound, so just break it off the bed as you normally would. The brim and support should pull away easily, leaving you with a ready-to-use panel.

I wanted to print each panel as one piece on the same machine they're installed on. To accomplish that goal, I designed this to be printed as a tower. I went through about 10 profile designs that failed at various heights before I tried this offset I-beam which stays remarkably rigid beyond 340mm. The slight tray effect on the outer surface also looks pretty good, in my opinion.

Several things didn't work. Made it about 4-inches free-standing before everything started coming apart. Playing with hands-on supports. First successful full-height print without external support.

description.text:
Feeder/Filament cooler for aluminium body Mk8 Extruders on Creality CR-10. On long prints with lots of retraction, thermal transmission from the warm stepper motor drive to the filament, can cause it to easily compress and go out of shape while its being fed, having seen that most Mk8's ship with a heat-sink covering the drive area, I decided to knock up this quick filament cooler, ensuring a flow of cool air over the filament, and around the head of the stepper motor.

Easily installed over a Mk8 extruder, and for the CR-10 in particular this acts as a handy cable guide for the wiring that runs up to the print head, may also be of use on some other printer designs perhaps, but the CR-10 with updated Metal feeder was my primary use for this.

description.text:
Goal was to a) experiment with the Voronoi style of 3D modeling and b) create a toothbrush holder that would actually come clean.

I've marked it as a "work in progress" not because I plan to develop it further but because...

  • the model files are too short; I scaled it in the Z axis in the slicer to about 110mm, near the limit of my Monoprice Select Mini
  • if you have toothbrushes with very wide handles/grips, you may need to enlarge the holes
  • The file names made sense at the time but might not now. See design notes

Printer:

Monoprice Select Mini

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.0875

Infill:

n.a.

Notes:

Scale Z axis non-unformly to 110mm or so!

Never really got the raft and supports fully cleaned up. Now that I have a different printer that does bridging better, I might try not using supports and the raft, but I don't need two toothbrush holders,

0.0875mm layer height was crazy overkill. Go with your default.

Enlarging holes

I was able to enlarge the top-center hole a little by softening that area with a heat gun and wiggling a dowel around the inside pushing out as it cooled.

FreeCAD: Basic form

If you redo this, consider making the height at least 2/3, maybe 3/4 of the length of your toothbrush handles. The current design is too short and must be printed with a scaled Z axis or it will be unbalanced. (Actually, the vertical elongation of the Voronoi pattern is not a bad look.)

I exported this form as a solid mesh, this is the "Toothbrush holder solid (Meshed).stl" file
(I also reexported as .obj from MeshMixer)

MeshMixer: Hollow out, reduce, cut holes, Voronoi

In Meshmixer, I imported the solid and hollowed it to 2mm. I'd been trying to go narrower, but the mesh broke too easily.

Then, using the select/edit/reduce dialog in Meshmixer reduce the number of polygones. Fewer polygons gives larger Voronoi shapes but increases the chances of breaking the mesh and making it unprintable. Be creative, and read/watch any of the many Voronoi modeling tutorials out there.

To make the holes in the top, I created three cylinders (given here as "Holes.stl"), positioned them above the indented base, and did a Boolean cut.

The final Meshmixer step -- after inspecting the mesh for defects and repairing -- is to edit/make pattern/dual edges. Again, please refer to tutorials online (I've only done this once and would not be a good instructor in this technique).

The file I exported after this is available here as "Toothbrush holder voronoi pattern 2mm.stl" (it's rather large, 86MB)

Scale, slice, print

After placing the .stl in Cura, I selected the object and scaled it in the Z axis only (turn off the Uniform Scaling checkbox) to 110mm high.

I printed it with a layer eight of only 0.0875, and gave it a raft. Took the Monoprice Select Mini v1 about 38 hours. (I got nervous when a thunderstorm came through... knowing it was going to take so long, I'd moved it to the garage, without its usual UPS)

Typical electric wheelchairs usually cost around 2,500$, and while it could turn around the life of whoever needs it, not everyone can justify spending such a grand amount of money, and are left stuck with rented wheelchairs. Our kit connects to standard rented wheelchairs without damaging them at that slightest and makes them mobile in a simplistic manner, for a fraction of the price, around 500$.

While every part of our kit can be bought separately, and be assembled using the tools in your disposal and a 3D printer, this kit has the added bonus of being comprised of parts which are abundant with every FRC team worldwide, meaning your local FRC team would be able to assemble your newly fashioned wheelchair.

FRC 1577

The team 1577 was founded in 2005 by its first mentor, Eyal Hershko, who brought the FRC to Israel for the first time.
Our team was one of the 12 first teams to compete in the Israeli Regional, and since then we continued competing for the last 10 years. We have a long heritage of professionalism, Persistence and the strive to be better as a team and as individuals.

Up to now, our team has included over 150 students that each has left their own unique mark and helped to build and design the nature of our team as we know it today.

Our team includes 31 high school members and 3 mentors that lead us and guide us based on their knowledge and experience. We learn from each other and from professionals that come in their free time to help and teach us in different subjects such as mechanics, programing, electronics, CAD, and strategy.

The specific team which worked on this kit consists of 3 students, each with their own distinct skills and expertise, such as Mechanics, Electronics and Programming, but we all had part in the general planning of the kit and we all helped each other in any way we could.
Over the span of a few weeks we have had frequent meetings, most of them at our own houses and during our own personal time.
During those couple of weeks we have had roughly 5 designs and 3 working prototypes, with totally different mechanics behind each idea.

General strategy for 3D ambigrams that work from two perpendicular angles:

Using Fusion 360, make text along two perpendicular planes. Explode both sets of text, then extrude one of the sets, then extrude the other using the intersect boolean operator. Add a base (if necessary), and the model is complete!

description.text:
The Aries is a rocket used by the military and by NASA from 1973 through the 1990's. It was made from the second stage of surplus Minuteman I missiles.

The first photo shows a model built mostly from stock Estes components (left), and the printed Aries (right).

It stands about 18.5" tall. When printed in MARS while PLA, the entire rocket weighs 6.7 ounces or 190 grams, compared to 4.7 ounces of the scratch-built model. Parts are joined with bayonet fittings that lock when you turn them clockwise just short of 90 degrees.

I have not flown this model, but I have added features to make it flyable. The removable nose tip will hold nose weight as deemed necessary for stable CG/CP relationship. The mid section has an internal shock cord lug, and the external fairing is open so it can be used as a launch lug. The fin section has a lip that will retain a motor mount with BT-80 centering rings. The forward ring would need to have four notches cut into it to clear the bayonet bumps when inserted. The rearmost ring can be tilted to get it past the bumps, and should probably not have notches in it because the ejection gases could escape there and prevent deployment of the parachute.

Thanks to Peter Alway and his "Rockets of the World" book for scale information on this rocket.

Update 12/27/2017: Added "Fin Section Hollow" - removed the internal structure to eliminate some weight.

Added "Fin+Mid Section.stl" and "Nose Cone Single Piece.stl". These can be used if you don't need to add nose weight, and don't need to separate the mid section from fin section. You still need to print the nose base.

ORION Delta 3D Printer

Rafts:

None

Notes:

See the uploaded Slic3r settings zip file.

Copy the Slic3r settings files into the filament/print/printer folders at
C:Users > yourID > AppData > Roaming > Slic3r .

You can use the Test Slice file to see if your settings are working for your printer. Use the fin section Slic3r settings, but set bottom solid layers to zero for the test slice. That parameter will need to be set back to 2 to print the entire fin section, so that the built-in supports will have good adhesion to the print bed.

Make sure you orient the parts as shown in the second photo to eliminate the need for supports. The fin section has built-in supports that break away easily.

The retraction settings are crucial for a clean print on a bowden-style printer. There are many travel moves in the fin section that can cause priming issues on the Orion and lead to under-extrusion in some spots. The extra-length on restart setting helped with that.

At 45mm/s, the fin section alone is a 4-hour print.

If you want to print at something other than 100% scale, remember that the nose and mid-section walls are 1.2mm thick allowing for two extrusions of ~.6mm, so you will need to adjust your extrusion width accordingly. Most of the fin section is solid with thin gaps that create the structural ribs. Scaling downward might result in those ribs not being printed.

If the bayonet connectors are tight, either sand them down or rub on some paraffin from a candle to lubricate them.

title: Anet A8 Enclosure for MKS Gen 1.4, MOSFET, Raspberry Pi

description.text:
I created this case to mount on the side of my Anet A8 and hold a MKS Gen V1.4 mainboard, Raspberry Pi 3, and a MOSFET for the heatbed.

Hardware:

  • 8 * M3 Nuts
  • 8 * M3 Washers (Recommended)
  • 8 * M3 x 12 Screws
  • 4 * M2 Nuts
  • 4 * M2 Washers (Recommended)
  • 4 * M2 x 12 Screws
  • 3 Screws and Nuts to attach to frame. (No particular size required. Test with your frame.)
  • 120mm Fan
  • 40mm Fan
  • Micro USB Left Angle Cable (https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00U2DGHP2)

The top is easy to attach and remove using the provided clips. They are different sizes and only fit snugly in each positions. (Two of them are the same size.)

You can mount the entire chassis after you install the boards. The mounting holes are not obscured by the boards.

This enclosure leaves room for the frame braces/stabilizers, such as the one I use: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2099154

As you can see from my photos, this chassis supports mounting an SDRamps adapter directly to the board and supports inserting and removing (using a tool).

There is some additional space still in the chassis for easy remixes.

  • For setting the sliding firmness of the wheels on the extrusion, I have added an m3 bolt hole. But instead of using an m3 nut I have used brass insert here:

  • For attaching the belt to the carriage you need to attach only the upper part of the belt to the gt2 teeth and leave 2-3cm open under the carriage. So you can use belt tightener included in files to make it tight.
  • Carriage has 50mm distance between the links when the rods are attached. You can use the effector here:
    https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2548508

description.text:
This is a remix to Anet A8 Extruder Fan Modification V2 by hadoko. I put a little more meat on the front bracket. The side bracket now holds a BL-Touch sensor.

The only thing is that you will need to change the offsets for this bracket. I had them as follows and they worked just fine:

define X_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER 14 // X offset: -left +right [of the nozzle]

define Y_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER 53 // Y offset: -front +behind [the nozzle]

define Z_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER 0 // Z offset: -below +above [the nozzle]

You travel limits will be different also. This is what I had for a 200x200 bed:
// Travel limits after homing (units are in mm)

define X_MAX_POS 220

define X_MIN_POS -33

define Y_MAX_POS 220

define Y_MIN_POS -10

define Z_MAX_POS 240

define Z_MIN_POS 0
